I'd like to quickly share some of my thoughts on the experience with DALMOOC, and right away I need to thank you Caroline, George, and Dragan, Ryan as well. I must say that up until this point I was truly forcing myself to stay with the course, as I needed to prove to myself that I can follow through, but the struggle comes mainly from the fact that I am an utter and complete novice when it comes to analytics. Therefore, I thank you guys for this wrap-up video which provided me with solace and relief, knowing that one can do just, say, material from week 1 and 2, or 2 and 4, etc., since until the hangout I had been under the impression that I am constantly far behind others. That feeling in tandem with my lack of experience or previous knowledge within the realm of analytics proved to make DALMOOC a truly daunting task. However, now when I've learnt that I can take it a bit easy, I can feel that the accompanying relief will prove boosting for my learning experience within the course.

On a slightly different note, to relate to what you said, namely that not as many participants of DALMOOC interact using various social platforms, I might know why this might be the case. Social cognition, decision-making, and elements along such lines are a passion of mine, and with that in mind I recently read an article, via TED, on choice across cultures.
In a nutshell, perhaps there's little interaction simply because course takers are allowed too much choice; even to me it feels quite overwhelming, making me feel a tad confused which channel to use to best connect with like-minded people, whether Google+, Twitter, Blog, Facebook, ProSolo, or EdX.
It was interesting that they said in the article that the best sense of community comes actually from conformity, in a way, resorting to not standing out but following others, knowing one's place, and therefore experiencing a sense of belonging, which I think is of paramount importance for one to feel at ease and thrive within a network. I'm not saying stifling creativity and choice at all cost, not at all so; but merely suggesting that perhaps choosing just on platform to interact with as a part of DALMOOC will make things easier to people, who already are bombarded with too much choices on a every day basis.

All in all, thank you once more for this hangout, and I hope you will find this feedback useful. Feel free to interact with me : )
I actually would like to use ProSolo, but I that perhaps there should be also a short video devoted to using ProSolo in an efficient and apt manner.
Lastly, I apologise for the lack of brevity.

Filip

I have taken almost a week to try and understand this competency, but I am still in darkness. I really need help on this one (Staff).

â€¢\tOutline different constructs from educational research/learning sciences that can be studied by using social network analysis methods

I have learned that doing social analysis network we can consider in education some constructs such as learning design, sense of community, creative potential, academic performance, and social presence.

-Learning Design: SNA provides useful information about students' actions within an online community. With that, teachers can design lessons, classroom-activities, and assessments.

- Sense of Community: SNA advises teachers when students are or are not participating in class, this is known as high or low level of sense of community. In the case that students do not have participated, it may mean that they do not feel part of the group. Having this information, teachers can support those students and encourage them to work harder and being part of a team. Otherwise, they could be prone to drop college.

- Creative Potential: SNA shows those students that have high level of centrality . Thet are known as brokers. Brokers are considering important connectors that have and share differents kind of information in their community. The literature says that those who have and share information on a network tend to be creatives because they are exposed to many different ideas, integrate them, and generate potentially novel solutions.

- Academic Performance: To those students that are highly related each other in a community (high centrality) are prone to have high academic performance.
